From a distance at the parking lot on Cliffside Dr, I saw a flock of birds take flight from the top of the hill at the point, rising a short height and settling back down, immediately suggesting Horned Larks. So we made a detour to climb to the top of the hill and there was a flock of Larks on the ground, and making short flights with much cheeping sounds. Seen well, and unmistakeable when seen well. Included about 50% adults and 50% fresh juveniles with cryptic spotting on the back. I counted 28 and Chef Ito counted 31 birds. The flock was eventually flushed by other hikers and flew northwest

Observation Details: Flock of four still around. Initially had them on the beach east of the second seaward pool but only on our way back. Birds were skittish and although they landed 30m away they took off and landed in the tilled field. We enjoyed nice scope views in the field before they were flushed by a numpty. This time they landed on the beach east of the first seaward pool. Here I snuck below the shingle ridge and crawled along the beach where I managed some reasonable shots at 20 m range. Unfortunately, they were then flushed by the same numpty as earlier, at which point I left them.  Birds looked rather pallid then when I last saw them, presumably due to wear and none of the birds showed any signs of horns yet.

Media notes: subspecies undetermined
Observation Details: Most appeared to be ssp. alpestris, one individual which was most likely ssp. praticola (but ssp. hoyti could not be ruled out). A few birds showed characters intermediate between subspecies.  The bird that appeared to be ssp. praticola was characterised by pale sandy brown, pink-peach washed upperparts, pale yellow centre throat, grading to white towards the ear coverts, white supercilium and a poorly defined black band across the lower throat which separated the yellow throat from the white underparts. Bird also showed a pale sandy brown breast band which was broken at the centre of the breast. Individual appeared similar in size to accompanying alpestris possibly a touch smaller.

Observation Details: As noted in comments, the map pin of this exact location is appearing in DC according to ebird's satellite imagery. I had reported a pair of Horned Larks, last weekend, on the other side of this runway (and closer to the main surface/runways of the airport). This Lark (8:45 am) was perched on a rock, at the top of the pilings, and was on the North side (visible side from Hains Point). I viewed it for about 2 minutes as it stood on this rock before a landing plane made it hop off and land further into this #33 runway area. It did not fly over the Potomac while I viewed it.

In road by red container.  I wonder about this bird.  I have seen it off and on for the last several trips and there is always only 1 horned lark, always in the vicinity of the red container. Observation Details: Continuing family. One adult carefully *not* feeding two chicks now. The adult (male? Heavy molt) was tolerating the chicks' presence and foraging on the ground at Loowit, on the slopes below the main lookout. When the adult would find a good bit of food (like a large grasshopper), the chicks would come running, but the adult would eat it instead. The chicks were pecking at grass/flower seeds, learning how to eat on their own. One was giving soft, plaintive calls as though still begging throughout the duration of the sighting. They're learning how to be independent now...

Infrequently encountered species within Pennsylvania's northeast region; always a treat to see! These individuals were seen foraging in a cornfield with recently spread cow manure. I have been checking this location frequently over the past two weeks with the hopes of finding Horned Lark along with SNBU & LALO, today was the first time I was successful! The farmer has been adding manure spreads to this field regularly; each time I visited this location there has been more manure than was present on the previous visits. These birds flew in from the east and were likely feeding at the neighboring "Drifting Lane Farm," one of the few remaining active Dairy Farms in Southern Wayne Co., prior to my encounter with them. All four individuals appeared to belong to the "Northern Horned Lark" subspecies complex.

Media notes: North American Horned Lark E. a. alpestris/hoyti/praticola
Observation Details: Female North American Horned Lark. Long staying bird that was found in late November and lingered then for a few  days. Relocated yesterday, quite lucky and really convenient for Heathrow. Gave great views on vegetated sides of Res from causeway. Compared to European birds more richly coloured pink-brown flanks, face showed mix of yellow and white feathering, with yellow mostly restricted to chin and throat, and white to sides of head and in particular to white supercilium, Breast showed conspicuous but diffuse brown spotting and streaking forming into rows extending down from black gorget below throat. Potentially first British record of bird from North American complex.

Observation Details: Noticeable increase in horned lark numbers at this road intersection. Very actively feeding on the remaining weeds that are still above snow. Locality: Back patio - Legend Hills - Prescott Valley, AZ. USA

Observation Details: From a distance at the parking lot on Cliffside Dr, I saw a flock of birds take flight from the top of the hill at the point, rising a short height and settling back down, immediately suggesting Horned Larks. So we made a detour to climb to the top of the hill and there was a flock of Larks on the ground, and making short flights with much cheeping sounds. Seen well, and unmistakeable when seen well. Included about 50% adults and 50% fresh juveniles with cryptic spotting on the back. I counted 28 and Chef Ito counted 31 birds. The flock was eventually flushed by other hikers and flew northwest

Observation Details: I was surprised to flush an individual from the wash, west of the stream and east of JPL.  I was able to track it down from flight calls and get photos -- a juvenile.  I was very surprised about an hour later to see a flock of 9 flying over the stream; i.d. based on flight calls, color (seen without binoculars), and flock flight style.  Given the multiple June sightings here over the years, I guess this location is in range of post-breeding dispersal.

Most of the attached photos were taken as the larks took furious dust-baths in the graveled lanes of the parking area next to the nature center.  The birds created furrows in the gravel with breasts and bellies, and pressing down into the hollows with tails raised and sometimes twisted, they writhed inside, sometimes turning their heads, with closed eyes, so that their bills pointed skyward.  The birds sometimes pecked rapidly at the front edge of the hollow.  I couldn't tell what they were aiming at. Maybe they were picking up grit, but the effect was to create clouds of tiny pebbles and dust that are sometimes visible in the photographs (and in other photographs, invisibly veil the head).  Their performances were interesting to watch with the naked eye, but their twists and turns occurred too quickly for the eye to make sense of them.   Because of their faces (which often have an angry look, in my opinion) one or two of the close-ups make them look as if they've very large and fierce.

photos: Colby says these are streaked subspecies of HOLA : looking at ebird options, which don’t list “streaked”, we assume “western rufous” prob is streaked? — at least 15 HOLA in field, at least 9 seen well up close to see are streaked form: breast streaking over warm tawny breast band color, and also another difference from Courtney’s Central Oregon type is these streaked today have reddish caps. We saw them close up enough that we also determined we couldn’t see any leg bands on these birds today, (unless perhaps some bands are found in Colby’s photos?) — in field beginning (44.4774,-123.2893) and to east of this pin ; — Colby says streaked are our typical westside valley type, and prob breed here we guess, and many are banded, and discussion with Caleb how remaining habitat for them is so limited that they might be listed as endangered soon, but even so this subspecies is surely “doomed”. — Sad,  sigh, they’re sweet. ... — (Colby 1.5-yr ago on Blueberry Ln in Oregon in ~ March had 3 different subspecies of HOLA there: streaked, and Courtney’s central Oregon type, and also the white-throated type)

Observation Details: Accepted as the American species, North American Horned Lark, however eBird doesn't have this as an accepted Species, this is a recent addition to the IOC British List.   The Lark showed well and periodically called along the dam wall feeding in the vegetation sometimes being very secretive. The bird differed from a Shore Lark with a white supercilluim extending down to a white 'cheek', pinkish flanks and rump. In some lights, mainly duller lights making the colours become truer, the bird also had a pink neck lace and pink in the coverts too. Very distinctive from Shore Lark.

Media notes: probably ssp. praticola
Observation Details: Most appeared to be ssp. alpestris, one individual which was most likely ssp. praticola (but ssp. hoyti could not be ruled out). A few birds showed characters intermediate between subspecies.  The bird that appeared to be ssp. praticola was characterised by pale sandy brown, pink-peach washed upperparts, pale yellow centre throat, grading to white towards the ear coverts, white supercilium and a poorly defined black band across the lower throat which separated the yellow throat from the white underparts. Bird also showed a pale sandy brown breast band which was broken at the centre of the breast. Individual appeared similar in size to accompanying alpestris possibly a touch smaller.

Infrequently encountered species within Pennsylvania's northeast region; always a treat to see! These individuals were seen foraging in a cornfield with recently spread cow manure. I have been checking this location frequently over the past two weeks with the hopes of finding Horned Lark along with SNBU & LALO, today was the first time I was successful! The farmer has been adding manure spreads to this field regularly; each time I visited this location there has been more manure than was present on the previous visits. These birds flew in from the east and were likely feeding at the neighboring "Drifting Lane Farm," one of the few remaining active Dairy Farms in Southern Wayne Co., prior to my encounter with them. All four individuals appeared to belong to the "Northern Horned Lark" subspecies complex.
